Sample

1st rowBased on the context provided, the following datasets are mentioned: * MovieLens * Netflix * MovieTweetings * MovieLens 100K
2nd rowSimon Dooms, Toon De Pessemier, and Luc Martens
3rd rowThis content is about a new movie rating dataset called 'MovieTweetings', which is constructed from public and well-structured tweets posted on Twitter. The paper presents this dataset as a modern and always up-to-date alternative to older datasets like MovieLens and Netflix, which are becoming outdated. The ratings are collected daily by querying the Twitter Search API for tweets containing the string ‘I rated’ and the hashtag ‘#IMDb’, which are typically auto-generated when a user rates a movie on the IMDb website and shares it. The paper provides metrics for the dataset, such as having over 60,000 ratings at the time of writing, and notes that it is unfiltered and available for download on GitHub.
4th rowPublic rating datasets like MovieLens and Netflix are becoming outdated and fail to incorporate new and relevant movies. This paper introduces a new movie rating dataset called ‘MovieTweetings,’ which is constructed from public, well-structured tweets. The data is collected daily from Twitter by searching for tweets containing the string ‘I rated’ and the hashtag ‘#IMDb’, which are auto-generated when users share their ratings from the IMDb website. The resulting dataset is unfiltered, updated daily with around 500 new ratings, and serves as a modern, natural rating resource for movie recommenders.
5th row* MovieLens * Netflix * MovieTweetings * MovieLens 100K
